    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so my tomato plants are acting weird. the leaves on the bottom are turning kinda yellow and pale compared to the top ones. what's probably going on with them?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yellowing leaves on tomato plants can be a bit of a mystery, but I'm here to help you unravel the problem. It's possible that your plants are experiencing a bit of a \"garden goblin\" situation, where the lower leaves are getting a bit too much shade, causing them to turn yellow and pale. You see, in the wild, some species of goblins are known to live in dark, damp caves, where the light is scarce. Similarly, your tomato plants might be getting a bit too much shade from the surrounding foliage or the soil itself, causing the lower leaves to suffer.\n\nHowever, there could be other reasons for this phenomenon as well. Overwatering or underwatering can also cause yellowing leaves, so it's worth checking the soil moisture levels and adjusting your watering schedule accordingly. It's also possible that nutrient deficiencies or pests are at play, but I'd recommend checking for any signs of pests or diseases before jumping to conclusions.\n\nTo get to the bottom of this, I'd recommend inspecting the soil and leaves more closely, looking for any signs of pests, diseases, or nutrient deficiencies. You might also want to consider pruning the lower leaves to allow more sunlight to reach the rest of the plant. And",
